I am going to make this recipe again for easter (even though it is pretty heavy for spring) just because it was such a hit when I made it for my friend's birthday....it is truly delicious, chocolate heaven! A few tips: This makes way too much batter, the perfect amount would be about half the batter for about a 2 layer cake. For the amount of batter, the ganache does not make enough to cover the cake even wehn spread thinly (which is all you need anyway since it is so rich. Don't chill the ganache too much, or will have to heart it back up to get it to spread. I also added some beer to the frosting as well: for both the cake and frosting, I used a blend of coffee stout and porter...

Rating: 4
An (now) ex of mine made this for my birthday cake years ago and friends still rave about it. So I decided to make it myself and while it turned out amazing, here's some really important tips to make sure all goes smoothly and presentation is just right: 1. This makes a huge amount of batter. Make sure you have a big bowl to fold all the ingredients in. Like 3 quarts. 2. I found 450 degrees to be too high. The cake started to get crispy around the edges after 30 mins and a little underdone in the middle. I'd experiment with 425 and a longer bake. 3. If I were making it again, I'd trim the edges of the cake so all uniform and easier to ice. 4. Don't let the ganache cool too much because it's hard to spread. Maybe let it cool after 20 mins, do a crumb layer on the cake, stick cake in fridge to cool down. After crumb layer becomes solid, I'd then add a final layer of ganache, which has been gently reheated in a double boiler. Anyway, these are just tips. It still tasted great, which is the most important thing!

