Rating: 4
I have made this cake three times. The first time it came out perfect - beginner's luck. The second time the center of the cakes fell but the taste was delicious. This time, the taste is amazing, but again the centers are a little low. Here is what I use: in icing, Scharffen Berger chocolate - half bittersweet (70%) and half semisweet (62%) [quality chocolate makes a difference]; in cake, Hershey's Special Dark cocoa [makes a dark rich cake]; beer, Guinness Extra Stout [I have bought other beers recommended in these reviews but I like the Guinness just as well]. Here are some lessons learned: 1. Quality chocolate matters in this recipe; 2. The cake tastes better after a day or even two - the beer flavor mellows and blends with the cake; 3. If your icing is too thin, it hasn't chilled long enough; 4. If your icing is lumpy, you haven't whisked it long enough; 5. If you ignore the icing like I did this time, it will harden like a rock. If that happens, you can heat it on the stove for a few seconds and then whip it to a usable consistency - you will get chocolate whipped cream but it will still taste great; 6. Sifting everything helps - sift your cocoa powder, flour, etc; 7. A generous coating of PAM baking spray in a good pan makes the cakes pop right out - no parchment paper needed; 8. Trust your instincts on the doneness of the cake - mine test done but look shiny in the middle, and I take them out and the middles fall. Next time I will try 325 instead of 350, and maybe a few minutes longer in the oven; 9. This cake freezes well. I take leftover slices and wrap well in press-and-seal and freeze that way. Enjoy!

