The first time that I made this recipe, the icing turned out as a glaze. Yesterday, it was a beautiful icing. I have no idea why they were different, except that I may have paid more attention to the icing this time (stirred it every half hour over a 4 hour cooling period in the fridge). I used Young's Double Chocolate Stout in the batter, but didn't notice that it tasted much different than the one I made with Murphy's. I cut the sugar to 3 cups and the butter to 3 sticks with no noticeable difference to the taste. Next time - and there will surely be a next time - I will try 2 sticks of butter and 2.5 cups of sugar.

Rating: 4
Oh my. Iced this cake last night and put it in the refrigerator, don't know if refrigeration was necessary. Just had a very thin sample this morning and it is amazing. Definitely a chocoholics dream come true! Can't wait to taste it after a day since reviewers say it is even better. Could not detect the Guinness, no one will guess the secret ingredient. A small piece is fine, it is very rich. I used Guinness Extra Stout, dutched cocoa and Guaradelli semi-sweet chips for the icing. And I did treat it as icing, chilling until it was icing consistency since I made 3 layers and wanted icing between each layer. Next time I may chill part for between the layers and use the rest as a ganache for the top. Made 3- 9" layers and that fit the pans perfectly. Baked at 350 for 40 minutes. Used waxed paper in the pans, sprayed with Baker's Secret, cooled for 10 minutes in pan and the layers popped right out. This cake has great possibilities for different icings, toppings and adaptations! The full recipe makes a huge (heavy!!) cake, but it is perfect for a large gathering.

