Rating: 4
I agree with everyone that this is a showstopping and delicious chocolate cake. Would give it 5 forks if I could. Here are some tips gleaned from making it many times. Use springform pans. Eliminates any chance of a problem getting layers out, guarantees very high layers without spills in the oven. Try using graduated pan sizes like a 10", 8" and 6" combination if you think one big tower isn't a look you like. Even with ordinary Hersheys cocoa and chocolate it is very very good but with high quality dutch process cocoa and Scharfenbarger it is sublime. Serve with a cream anglaise or the topping from the Guiness Goodness receipe also on this site for a nice presentation on the plate. I am not a particularly good baker, tend not to measure carefully, and yet this cake is incredible every time. If it doesn't work for you, you really have done something wrong and should try again (maybe with fresh ingredients?). Put the sour cream and egg in your largest mixing bowl, there will be something like 16 cups of batter when you are done. Sometimes I have whipped the ganache and put it only between the layers leaving the sides exposed. This is the cake you will become famous for.

Rating: 3
The cake part of this recipe is amazing. It's not too sweet and you can subtly taste the stout. The first time I made this I followed the recipe exactly. I thought the icing overpowered the cake. I think having 3 layers with all that icing is too much. I've since made a 9x13 single layer cake with a little icing on top. I left the cake in the pan so I didn't need to wait for the icing to cool and stiffen before pouring the icing on. I've also just made the cake part in various pans (9x13, bundt, 7x11). It's excellent without any icing. I've noticed that the cake improves with time. I recommend eating it a day after you make it. It's a lot moister.

