Rating: 4
Here is the frosting trick, borrowed from Martha Stewart's wedding book in the 80s.(her recipe for a chocolate grooms cake) Make the ganache as directed but let it cool to room temperature. DON'T put it in the fridge. Get out your beaters and whip the room temp ganache until it starts to get light -- it will not be like whipped cream, but it will be lighter and more spreadable than chilled ganache. Use that as the icing. It will NOT harden up like a truffle. It will be a little more dense than buttercream, but wonderful. If you want a glossy chocolate coat, make more ganache following the recipe (essentially, half and half cream and dark chocolate) and pour it over the iced cake after it cools (dont pour it over too hot or it will melt the ganache already on the cake). I made this cake on a saturday night for a Monday dinner, kept it under a dome and it was fresh and perfect when I cut into it. Really wonderful recipe; yields an enormous, impressive 3 layer cake. And I heartily second "the most delicious batter" pronouncement.

Rating: 4
