Rating: 4
My only quibble with this recipe is that the "icing" is actually a chocolate ganache, It doesn't set up like regular icing because it's essentially the same thing as chocolate truffle, and while it is nice and runny and glossy when warm, it will turn quite hard and truffle-like if allowed to sit. So I don't recommend the recipe's method of allowing the recipe to set up, and also, you probably will find the icing too stiff to put in a pastry bag. Ideally, you pour it over the cake layers and spread it out with an offset spatula or some other long flat cake spatula. (Using a mold to bake the cake, like a cathedral mold, will severely complicate this task and I do not recommend it unless you are capable of pouring with a very even, light hand while the ganache is still fairly warm). It's best to set the assembled cake layers on a wire rack set over a pan before pouring the ganache over the center of the assembled cake. Smooth the ganache out on top and let the excess ganache run over the sides. Smooth it out on the sides as it coats them. If the ganache has set up too much, reheat it in a double boiler and add a little more cream if necessary. To the cook who plans to see if it will "soften up" and be piped out of a pastry bag - I wouldn't try. If you are committed to doing something like that, either use my reheating method and fill the bag while the ganache is quite warm, or, after reheating, allow it to cool to about 120degrees and beat it in a thin stream into 2 sticks of butter that you have creamed until very fluffy. That might help soften it out enough. The cake was delicious. I halved the recipe and baked it in a 10" springform pan for 45 minutes when I realized two of my round cake pans had gone missing. After cooling and removing from the pan, I split it into two layers and made a two-layer, instead of the specified 3-layer, cake (which would have been huge).

