The cake was good, not as great as I expected though. I'm a true chocoholic and I didn't think it was dense enough. I made half the recipe, baked it in a bundt pan (non-stick, Criscoed and floured, had no problem getting it out of the pan) and left off the frosting, maybe next time I'll try it with the frosting. I used Young's Double Chocolate Stout and Droste cocoa powder, also, I frequently find most dessert recipes too sweet, so I usually cut the sugar by a quarter to a third, I used the full amount of sugar called for in this recipe and didn't think it was too sweet, as the stout cut the sweetness. For Thanksgiving I'm going to try the Double Chocolate layer cake (on this site), which many here have recommended, it uses about twice as much chocolate.

Rating: 4
This recipe was by far the most amazing chocolate cake I have ever tasted and/or made. I read all the reviews, which helped. I used extra stout Guinness (did not taste yeasty at all), half dutch processed store brand cocoa and half Ghiradelli (sp?) which was not dutch processed. Last 1/3 of a cup of sour cream was the light kind, I bought a too small container of the regular. I made 3- 9 inch layers (3 cups batter per pan) and 2- 8 inch layers. Baked at 325 instead of 350 (personal preference for layer cakes, I find that it produces a more level cake) and they were done in about 32 minutes. Froze the two 8 inch layers and frosted the 3 9 inch layers with a half recipe of the ganache. It was *just* enough ganache and set up no problem in my fridge in about 2 1/2 hours. Brought it to a dinner party, was told it was "good enough to sell". Yummy. The only problem I had was that I forgot the parchement paper and just used my standard shortening and flour that I keep pre-mixed. My 9 inch layers came out no problem after 10 minutes, but I got distracted on the 8 inch layers and left them in for about 20 minutes, so one broke up on de-panning. The moral is that you don't need the parchment if you are diligent about watching the time. While this is a very decadent and somewhat expensive cake, it was extremely easy to put together. I use a kitchen scale to ensure my pans are equally filled.

