Loved the taste of this cake - very moist, not too sweet. Did not have 2" sides, so used the standard 1 1/2" sides and removed 2 cupcakes worth of batter so as not to overflow. Worked great. Had to cook cakes about 42 minutes for the ones in center of oven, 45 minutes for top of oven. No parchment needed, just use good non-stick pans with butter and tap gently out. Husband thought to throw last of his beer into batter as a joke (about 1/2 cup), but didn't affect batter. At last second I realized I didn't have enough chocolate for frosting, but 12 oz. choc w/ 1 1/2 c. of whipping cream was just enough for a thin layer for the whole cake.

Rating: 4
This recipe halves easily -- more beer left over for the cook! ;-) I use a bundt pan when I make this as a half recipe. All it needs when done is a simple dusting of powdered sugar. Once you assemble the ingredients and get the pan ready, this is a simple cake to put together. I think this cake stays moist and delicious longer than most cakes. Flavor deepens the next day. An all-around great cake!

Rating: 4
This is a GREAT cake. Dense, moist and not sickening sweet like some cakes, although it's certainly not for the faint of heart! Worth every calorie!

Rating: 4
This cake is fantastic. I made this first for a large family gathering about a year ago, and ever since then I am asked to make it for every family get-together. It does make a HUGE amount of cake, but I also think it is fun to walk in with an eight inch tall chocolate cake. It comes out very dense but not overly sweet. The stout gives it a deep flavor that sets it apart from other traditional chocolate cakes. One cake should be able to serve a large group. Highly recommended.

Rating: 4
My, was this good! I forgot to buy cream for the icing, so I made it in two loaf pans and added some bittersweet chocolate chips. This is really heavenly - so much darker and moister than I expected. I also was out of granulated sugar, so I had to use 'Sugar in the Raw'. The texture was fine despite of this, in fact it was fabulous. I didn't notice a pronounced flavor from the stout. It seemed to mellow the chocolate flavors and made it less sweet. I will be making this cake again and again. I forgot to mention on earlier post that I halved the recipe, otherwise there is no way this would fit in two loaf pans!

Rating: 4
This is now my chocolate cake. I made as a birthday cake--made half the recipe and baked in two standard 8 inch pans (i.e., 1-1/2 inch sides, not 2 inch sides, which you have to buy at a cookware store). Baked layers for 1/2 hour. Perfect!!! The frosting was a little soft, but still great (used Valrhona from good old Trader Joes). I buttered pans, put parchment on bottom and buttered and floured pan and had no problem with sticking layers. Yummy!!!

Rating: 4
Just one word-- DEELISH. I ended up with four layers; used three for a friend's birthday cake and one for our Valentine's Day treat. Not only does this cake look impressive, swirled with ganache, but it's a fabulous adult dessert. (With three children, we sometimes get a little tired of super-sweet, simple kid cakes.) I didn't use parchment, just sprayed the pans with Baker's Joy and had no problems with sticking. Can't wait for another big occasion to make this again. A tiny sliver satisfies, so you can get a lot of pieces from the cake. YUM!

Rating: 3
boy does this make A LOT of cake. i did not have a bowl big enough for the batter so i mixed it by hand in a dutch oven. the cake was delicious and sufficiently chocolaty. i used a double chocolate stout i found at trader joes. i didn't have the right pan's called for so i made 12 cupcakes, a 2 layer round 8 in diameter cake, and a 8 in square cake(as i said, a lot of cake). i didn't bother with the frosting (although if i wasn't a cheap college student i would have), just used whipped cream.

Rating: 4
Fantastic recipe, rates as my #2 recipe for chocolate cake (#1 is recipe Double Chocolate Layer Cake 101275 on this site). I think that this recipe is more 'adult' with a stronger, deeper and more intense flavour. People that love it will accept nothing else. But there will be those that won't, so my #1 choice is a more sure bet it my opinion. Regarding what a reviewer wrote below, I think all Guiness are called "extra stout". That's what I used and it didn't taste at all like yeast. Ganache recipe is simple and good. Overall this recipe uses slightly less ingredients and takes less effort to make, but costs quite a bit more due to the Guiness.

Rating: 4
I made this for a large gathering at our house, and it was quite a success--very intense and rich, a totally satisfying chocolate cake. I bake a lot, and consider chocolate cake the ultimate dessert, and I'll definitely add this to my repertoire of 3-4 recipes I turn to, depending on the occasion. It is HUGE, a very high cake. I have 9-inch pans, and still seemed like way too much batter, but it worked. Took longer to bake and still fell a bit in middles of layers, but didn't ruin the look. A home-brewing friend had some coffee stout he wasn't totally satisfied with for drinking, so I used that, and it worked great.

Rating: 4
I made this last August, knew I had lost the recipe and could probably find it here. The cake is huge, impressive and delicious. My daughters are still raving about the cake.

Rating: 1
I wish I had read reviews before I made this cake. I can bake anything, so decided to make this cake for a party where I knew there would be some beer makers who appreciate stout. The cake was a total disaster--layers stuck to the pan and the parchment, and fell apart when I tried to put one on top of another. I have been able to rescue cakes when this has happened in the past, but it has never been this bad--the cake just fell apart! In adition, the frosting was not set after 3 hours in the refrigerator, even though the recipe suggests 2 hours.I managed to patch half of the cake together because the taste was good--it looked horrible. I have a big pile of chocolate mess in my kitchen that I will probably throw away, and a dent in my reputation as a gourmet baker.

Rating: 3
I've made this recipie several times. It makes a very large cake, but it freezes very well, so make extra layers! To help with frosting the cake, try freezing the cake first. This will help get that crumb layer of frosting on. Also, freezing the finished cake is a great way of transporting without much danger of ruining the decoration.

Rating: 3
I gave this recipe 3 forks based on potential only. I made it for a party and absolutely no one liked it. I'm an experienced baker, but know nothing about beer. When I looked for stout, all I could find was Guinness Extra Stout. Perhaps, I should have used regular Guinness which is not labeled stout on the bottle. Anyway, the cake tasted of yeast. Several people commented on it and I did not tell them what was in it. All that aside the cake's texture and sweetness is perfect. The amount of frosting seemed a bit skimpy, so I made 25% more. I would like to try this recipe with the regular Guinness. It has great potential.

Rating: 4
This cake was wonderful. It's easy to make yet the taste is so sophisticated. My favorite thing about the cake is the way it tastes VERY chocolatey but not too sweet. One note: you may want to wait until after people have had a piece to tell them about the Guiness. It freaks some people out.

Rating: 4
This recipe is wonderful. Currently living in Japan and attempting to bake without a Western-style oven, I steamed this cake. I was extremely impressed with the texture and subtle flavor of the cake. I certainly will make it again.

Rating: 2
I was very excited to try this cake. I am a pretty proficient cake baker but had some trouble with this cake. I cut the recipe in half because I did not want the huge cake that everyone described. Maybe that was the problem, halving the recipe. The cake stuck to the buttered parchment paper( I have never had that happen before) and I had cooled it properly etc. It was very crumbly and the second layer actually broke in half when I tried to put it on top of the first layer. Doing the crumb coat of icing was almost impossible and the cake looked awful. Having said all that, I quite liked the taste and it was moist. My husband hated it and suggested I stick with my regular tried and true chocolate cake. I wonder, has anyone else halved it with the same results????? I almost think I will try it again following the recipe exactly.It got so many good reviews I feel it deserves another chance.

Rating: 4
This is cake is rich, dense and delicious! Restaurant quality! I make three layers in 9 inch cake pans and it turned out perfectly. I started with the frosting and make it as written - if you leave it in the fridge and stir occasionally it will be the right consistency by the time your cake is mixed, baked and cooled. Do use quality chocolate for the frosting. I normally would use Lindt, but bought Nestle instead and wasn't as impressed. Enjoy!!!

Rating: 4
Found the cake to be very big, actually wonder if it would work better in 9" pans, it was so tall! Anyway it was absolutely delicious, took it to a dinner party and everyone raved about, I now have emailed the host the recipe. Tasted even better the second day. A definite keeper.

Rating: 4
Run, don't walk, to the store and buy Guinness now! I made this cake for my wife's birthday and she thought it was delicious. Do not be afraid of the stout. It adds a tremendous density to the cake both in terms of color and texture. I plan to make this cake for St. Patrick's Day. I modified the frosting to make it a bit thicker. I added confectioners sugar and beat it on high for three minutes or so, and then chilled it for a couple of hours. It worked great.

Rating: 4
This recipe is simply fabulous. The resulting cake using the 8" pans is very large (plan ahead on how to store it -- it did not fit in any of my standard cake keepers). It is rich, very chocolately tasting cake with a great consistency. It does improve overnight and the flavor seems to intensify. Definitely a keeper!

Rating: 4
This is a yummy chocolate cake recipe for any chocoholics. I was skeptical when I poured the batter into the cake pan - it was watery and bubbly (from the stout). The icing was a little too thin to spread but after refridgerating the iced cake overnight, the icing was just right for the very moist and decadent cake. Very good recipe, this.

Rating: 4
This cake is the best. I didn't quite get the frosting right. It was too thin to spread. So I added a package of softened cream cheese, more confectioner's sugar, 1 tsp of vanilla and beat on high. It came out wonderful.

Rating: 3
I love chocolate cake, as does my son, this cake is delicious! I actually forgot to add the baking soda ( I was using 2-9inch pans and 3/4 the recipe and got distracted doing the math) anyway, and put them in the oven and realized it about 5 minutes later, took them out, dumped the batter back into the bowl, added the soda, put them back in, and it STILL came out wonderful.

Rating: 4
THIS RECIPE IS FANTASTIC. I WAS AFRAID OF THE BEER, BUT THE CAKE TURNED OUT THICK, RICH AND SOPHISTICATED. I MADE IT FOR A BIRTHDAY PARTY, AND THE FINISHED CAKE WAS 7" HIGH. THE GANACHE WAS SO FLUFFY AND THE CAKE SO MOIST THAT IT DIDN'T EVEN NEED A CRUMBCOAT. I USED 9" X 2" PANS. AFTER MAKING THE GANACHE I FROZE IT FOR ONE HOUR & BEAT IT ON HIGH SPEED FOR THREE MINS BEFORE FROSTING. MAKE THIS CAKE!

